The National Security Advisors of the United States, Japan, and the Philippines recently met in Tokyo to discuss trilateral cooperation. They emphasized the importance of deepening cooperation to maintain a free and open international order. The NSAs highlighted the need to enhance response capabilities based on existing alliances in order to ensure peace and stability in the Indo-Pacific region. They also discussed regional security challenges, such as the South China Sea, the East China Sea, North Korea, and the Taiwan Strait. The NSAs confirmed plans to enhance trilateral cooperation in defense and security, maintaining a free and open maritime order, humanitarian assistance and disaster relief, and promoting a free and equitable economic order. They agreed to hold further trilateral exchanges in the future to expand cooperation and information-sharing.